The Andrew Oldham Orchestra was a musical side project in the mid-1960s created by
Andrew Loog Oldham, the original manager and record producer of The Rolling Stones.
There was no actual orchestra per se. The name was applied to recordings made by
Oldham using a multitude of session musicians, including members of the Rolling Stones.

The Rolling Stones Songbook included an orchestral version of the Mick Jagger and
Keith Richards song "The Last Time", which was sampled by The Verve for their
track "Bitter Sweet Symphony". The threat of litigation over the license for the
sample led to the entire copyright to the composition, belonging to Richard Ashcroft,
The Verve's frontman, being taken by ABKCO Records, and the sharing of the songwriting
credit with Jagger and Richards, even though they didn't compose the string segment
that The Verve sampleds
